metadata.name: Heima #18
metadata.description:
Heima is an Icelandic word that means “at home”. It can refer to the place where someone lives, but it can also have a more abstract meaning, such as a sense of belonging and connection to one’s roots.

The art project wants to explore this concept of home and belonging, starting from the role that the house plays in Nordic culture. In many northern european countries there is a strong sense of community and a focus on social connections and the home is often seen as a place where these connections are cultivated and maintained.

- - -

A reserve list will be generated from the holders of my previous project "Fifty Windows".
The reserve list will be closed 24h before the mint.

Each "Heima" minter will get 10% of royalties from secondary market.

- - -

Learn more:

https://medium.com/@detegus/heima-ac1f91ccd329

- - -

Keyboard shortcuts

- Press [1] to save at 5000 x 5000 px resolution
- Press [2] to save at 10000 x 10000 px resolution
- Press [3] to save at 15000 x 15000 px resolution

metadata.name: Décollage #275
metadata.description:
A generative sketch based on the concept of décollage, an artistic process that involves cutting or tearing pieces of an original image. The resulting outputs bear a resemblance to artworks produced using the lacerated poster technique, where posters are layered and torn to reveal parts of the posters underneath.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels. Note that this will not work with sizes beyond 5000 pixels.

(Allowlist is based on quantity of previous works owned).

metadata.name: Randos #249
metadata.description:
Meet Randos. Generative PFP ready pictures. Each Rando has unique features and a rando-id made up of a random 3 letter word + a number. See if you can get a scrabble-friendly word. Each Rando also has a frequently used word/phrase. Inspired by the Xcopy style flashing imagery, glitch art, and color pallete.


Click on the image to save a frame.
Please mint only a few as it's a free mint.

metadata.name: intermission #74
metadata.description:
'intermission' is an artwork that thats based on the distinct structuring of onethousendsixhundred circles. their arrangement within a calm defined pattern, leads to an effect of waviness with every generated color-palette.   while the pattern stays static, it’s the randomised colors which create a very unique character within every single generated piece.   

as i find there is a high number of great colorcombinations, i made the iteration number high, but the floor low.

 pressing 's' lets you save a .png file

if you like 'intermission' mint a piece or two, fall in love with its colors, spread the love!!!

metadata.name: Nekonečné Pylóny #5
metadata.description:
A march; the endless light strike.
Electric tall, but height unknowable.
In striated metal branches, across this
distance.

Energy makes a mockery of the magician, like
the steel-shod flea of Tulsa.

-- FEATURES --

Coloured background and contrasting lines.
Divisions generated from hash.
Rotation, and a sense of the endless void.
Heat death of universe not specifically included, but inevitable.

metadata.name: L-2D CA #103
metadata.description:
Audiovisual architecture of a two dimensional cellular automation. An initial randomisation process is followed by a layering ritual. Time = space: cell states are locked into their corresponding positions on the elevation axis.

Touch to listen.

metadata.name: Wall Drawing #42
metadata.description:
1. Remember to stay focused on your dilemma or subject or question when casting.

2. Hold the lines loosely in your hands, shake them briefly, and then toss them, all the while contemplating your query. The line you record is determined by assigning numerical values to heads and tails, then adding the total. 

3. Collect the lines and toss another n times, recording the numerical values and the corresponding line each time, building your n+1-line hexagram from the bottom up.

Hommáge to S. L.
